<subSubSection id="8FAA1E8DFFB6FF88FD2F275CFF79889A" lastPageId="40" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="37" pageNumber="37" type="description">
<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFB6FF86FD2F275CFE858C10" blockId="37.[704,1233,1036,1763]" lastBlockId="38.[94,623,1182,1763]" lastPageId="38" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="37" pageNumber="37">
IDENTIFICATION: Descriptions and measurements of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB6FF85FCB7277EFBC68CB8" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[837,1101,1388,1411]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB6FF85FCB7277EFBC68CB8" box="[837,1101,1388,1411]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="37">Saccopteryx bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Guianas and elsewhere were provided by Thomas (1904), Sanborn (1937), 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFB6FF85FB9627B4FC4A8CE0" author="Goodwin, G. G. &amp; A. M. Greenhall" journalOrPublisher="Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist." pageId="37" pageNumber="37" pagination="191 - 301" part="122" refId="ref94360" refString="Goodwin, G. G., and A. M. Greenhall 1961. A review of the bats of Trinidad and Tobago: descriptions, rabies infection, and ecology. Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist. 122: 191 - 301." title="A review of the bats of Trinidad and Tobago: descriptions, rabies infection, and ecology" type="journal article" year="1961">Goodwin and Greenhall (1961)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFB6FF85FC3D27D6FBFC8CE0" author="Husson, A. M." bookContentInfo="282 pp." box="[975,1143,1476,1499]" journalOrPublisher="Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52" pageId="37" pageNumber="37" refId="ref95767" refString="Husson, A. M. 1962. The bats of Suriname. Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52: 282 pp. 1 30 pls." title="The bats of Suriname" type="book" year="1962">Husson (1962</bibRefCitation>
, 1978), and 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFB6FF85FD0727F3FB468CC3" author="Brosset, A. &amp; P. Charles-Dominique" box="[757,1229,1505,1528]" journalOrPublisher="Mammalia" pageId="37" pageNumber="37" pagination="509 - 559" part="54" refId="ref91807" refString="Brosset, A., and P. Charles-Dominique 1990. The bats from French Guiana: a taxonomic, faunistic and ecological approach. Mammalia 54: 509 - 559." title="The bats from French Guiana: a taxonomic, faunistic and ecological approach" type="journal article" year="1990">Brosset and CharlesÂ­Dominique (1990)</bibRefCitation>
. There is considerable disagreement concerning trinomial nomenclature. Thomas (1904) explicitly recognized only two subspecies, 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB6FF85FB48242BFB428F6B" box="[1210,1225,1593,1616]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="37">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB6FF85FD322445FD448F55" box="[704,719,1623,1646]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="37">b</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB6FF85FD102445FCC28F55" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[738,841,1623,1646]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB6FF85FD102445FCC28F55" box="[738,841,1623,1646]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="37">bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in northern South America (including Trinidad), and 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB6FF85FC3C2466FC568FB0" box="[974,989,1652,1675]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="37">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB6FF85FC1F2466FC778FB0" box="[1005,1020,1652,1675]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="37">b</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB6FF85FBF92466FBFA8FB0" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1912" box="[1035,1137,1652,1675]" class="Mammalia" family="Molossidae" genus="Promops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="centralis">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB6FF85FBF92466FBFA8FB0" box="[1035,1137,1652,1675]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="37">centralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Central America. Subsequently, Sanborn (1937) argued that size variation in this species was continuously distributed and precluded delinÂ­ eation of subspecies in the absence of other significant characters; in his revision, the names 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FF4426CBFE9B8DCB" box="[182,272,1241,1264]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">insignis</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FED426CBFE378DCB" box="[294,444,1241,1264]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perspicillifer">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FED426CBFE378DCB" box="[294,444,1241,1264]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">perspicillifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FDFB26CBFDE48DCB" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1912" box="[521,623,1241,1264]" class="Mammalia" family="Molossidae" genus="Promops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="centralis">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FDFB26CBFDE48DCB" box="[521,623,1241,1264]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">centralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were therefore regarded as strict synonyms of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FF722706FE8C8C10" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[128,263,1300,1323]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FF722706FF048C10" box="[128,143,1300,1323]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FF522706FE8C8C10" box="[160,263,1300,1323]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFB5FF86FF892723FEE68FFE" blockId="38.[94,623,1182,1763]" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">
Although many authors have followed Sanbornâs (1937) opinion (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFB5FF86FDFB275CFF148CB8" author="Husson, A. M." bookContentInfo="282 pp." journalOrPublisher="Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" refId="ref95767" refString="Husson, A. M. 1962. The bats of Suriname. Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52: 282 pp. 1 30 pls." title="The bats of Suriname" type="book" year="1962">Husson, 1962</bibRefCitation>
, 1978), others have not. 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFB5FF86FDFE277EFF258C9B" author="Cabrera, A." bookContentInfo="307 pp." journalOrPublisher="Rev. Museo Argent. Cienc. Nat. '' Bernardino Rivadavia' ' (Cienc. Zool.) 4" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" refId="ref91973" refString="Cabrera, A. 1958. Catalogo de los mamiferos de America del Sur. Rev. Museo Argent. Cienc. Nat. '' Bernardino Rivadavia' ' (Cienc. Zool.) 4 (1): 307 pp." title="Catalogo de los mamiferos de America del Sur" type="book" year="1958">Cabrera (1958)</bibRefCitation>
, for example, recognized 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FE13279BFF058C85" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perspicillifer">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FE13279BFE7B8C9B" box="[481,496,1417,1440]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FE0D279BFF058C85" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">perspicillifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(from Trinidad) as a distinct species, and 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFB5FF86FFAC27D6FE5D8CE0" author="Goodwin, G. G. &amp; A. M. Greenhall" box="[94,470,1476,1499]" journalOrPublisher="Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist." pageId="38" pageNumber="38" pagination="191 - 301" part="122" refId="ref94360" refString="Goodwin, G. G., and A. M. Greenhall 1961. A review of the bats of Trinidad and Tobago: descriptions, rabies infection, and ecology. Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist. 122: 191 - 301." title="A review of the bats of Trinidad and Tobago: descriptions, rabies infection, and ecology" type="journal article" year="1961">Goodwin and Greenhall (1961)</bibRefCitation>
later treated 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FFAC27F3FF7F8CC3" box="[94,244,1505,1528]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perspicillifer">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FFAC27F3FF7F8CC3" box="[94,244,1505,1528]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">perspicillifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FDED27F3FF148F2D" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FDED27F3FDA58CC3" box="[543,558,1505,1528]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FDCF27F3FF148F2D" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Most recently, Koopman (1994) recognized 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FF31240EFF598F08" box="[195,210,1564,1587]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FF10240EFF7A8F08" box="[226,241,1564,1587]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">b</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FEF3240EFEE38F08" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[257,360,1564,1587]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FEF3240EFEE38F08" box="[257,360,1564,1587]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as ranging from tropical Mexico throughout Central America and tropical South America except northern Venezuela, Trinidad, and Tobago, and 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FE0F2466FD878FB0" box="[509,524,1652,1675]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FDEF2466FDA78FB0" box="[541,556,1652,1675]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">b</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FDCF2466FF468F93" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perspicillifer">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FDCF2466FF468F93" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">perspicillifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as occuring in northern Venezuela, Trinidad, and Tobago).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFB5FF88FF8924DEFD848830" blockId="38.[94,623,1182,1763]" lastBlockId="40.[94,623,214,1763]" lastPageId="40" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">
Recognition of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FEB024DEFE538FD8" box="[322,472,1740,1763]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="perspicillifer">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FEB024DEFE538FD8" box="[322,472,1740,1763]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">perspicillifer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a taxon distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FCB8268DFC3A8D8D" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[842,945,1183,1206]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FCB8268DFC3A8D8D" box="[842,945,1183,1206]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is apparently based entirely on size, with specimens from northern Venezuela, Trinidad (the type locality), and Tobago supposedly being larger and more robust than specimens from elsewhere in the Neotropics (
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFB5FF86FC622723FBA68C73" author="Miller, G. S." box="[912,1069,1329,1352]" journalOrPublisher="Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist." pageId="38" pageNumber="38" pagination="173 - 181" part="12" refId="ref98056" refString="Miller, G. S. 1899. Descriptions of three new free-tailed bats. Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist. 12: 173 - 181." title="Descriptions of three new free-tailed bats" type="journal article" year="1899">Miller, 1899</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFB5FF86FBB02723FC1A8C5E" author="Goodwin, G. G. &amp; A. M. Greenhall" journalOrPublisher="Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist." pageId="38" pageNumber="38" pagination="191 - 301" part="122" refId="ref94360" refString="Goodwin, G. G., and A. M. Greenhall 1961. A review of the bats of Trinidad and Tobago: descriptions, rabies infection, and ecology. Bull. Am. Mus. Nat. Hist. 122: 191 - 301." title="A review of the bats of Trinidad and Tobago: descriptions, rabies infection, and ecology" type="journal article" year="1961">Goodwin and Greenhall, 1961</bibRefCitation>
). However, this putative geographic pattern is not supported by available data. Instead, our personal observations and data reported by Thomas (1904), Sanborn (1937), 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFB5FF86FCC527D6FC568CE0" author="Husson, A. M." bookContentInfo="282 pp." box="[823,989,1476,1499]" journalOrPublisher="Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" refId="ref95767" refString="Husson, A. M. 1962. The bats of Suriname. Zool. Verh. Rijksmus. Nat. Hist. (Leiden) 52: 282 pp. 1 30 pls." title="The bats of Suriname" type="book" year="1962">Husson (1962</bibRefCitation>
, 1978), and 
<bibRefCitation id="A32130F7FFB5FF86FB9F27D6FBCF8CC3" author="Brosset, A. &amp; P. Charles-Dominique" journalOrPublisher="Mammalia" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" pagination="509 - 559" part="54" refId="ref91807" refString="Brosset, A., and P. Charles-Dominique 1990. The bats from French Guiana: a taxonomic, faunistic and ecological approach. Mammalia 54: 509 - 559." title="The bats from French Guiana: a taxonomic, faunistic and ecological approach" type="journal article" year="1990">Brosset and CharlesÂ­Dominique (1990)</bibRefCitation>
indicate that specimens from eastern Ecuador, Guyana, Surinam, French Guiana, Brazil, and Bolivia exhibit similar forearm, skull, and dental measurements as specimens from northern Venezuela, Trinidad, and Tobago. Thus, although significant geographic variation may exist among some populations of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFB5FF86FD6C24DEFC118FD8" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[670,922,1740,1763]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFB5FF86FD6C24DEFC118FD8" box="[670,922,1740,1763]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="38">Saccopteryx bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, none of the subspecies traditionally recognized by authors appear to be justified by the evidence at hand.
</paragraph>
