<subSubSection id="8FAA1E8DFFBBFF88FF8923B5FE1D8FD8" pageId="40" pageNumber="40" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFBBFF88FF8923B5FDA98AE3" blockId="40.[94,623,214,1763]" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">
FIELD OBSERVATIONS: We recorded 34 captures (possibly including some recaptures) of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFBBFF88FFAC23F1FEEE88C1" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[94,357,483,506]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBBFF88FFAC23F1FEEE88C1" box="[94,357,483,506]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">Saccopteryx bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 14 in groundÂ­level mistnets, 11 in elevated mistnets, and 9 at roosts; additionally, 1 specimen was recovered from the crop of a roadÂ­killed 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBBFF88FE0D202FFF348B49" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">Falco rufigularis</emphasis>
(which had also eaten a specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFBBFF88FFAC206BFF5F8BAB" baseAuthorityName="Schreber" baseAuthorityYear="1774" box="[94,212,632,656]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leptura">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBBFF88FFAC206BFFE68BAB" box="[94,109,633,656]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBBFF88FF72206BFF5F8BAB" box="[128,212,633,656]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">leptura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Of the 14 groundÂ­level mistnet captures, 4 were made in wellÂ­drained primary forest, 2 in swampy primary forest, 3 in creekside primary forest, and 5 in manmade clearings. Six 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFBBFF88FEA520E2FE548A3C" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[343,479,752,775]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBBFF88FEA520E2FEED8A3C" box="[343,358,752,775]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBBFF88FE8A20E2FE548A3C" box="[376,479,752,775]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were taken in nets suspended 10â21 m over a narrow dirt road, two were netted 10â13 m over a treefall gap in creekside primary forest, and three were netted 7â10 m above the ground in the subcanopy of swampy primary forest. Six of our mistnet captures were made before dark, between 18:00 and 18:35 hours.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C70F4D06FFBBFF88FF8921CDFE1D8FD8" blockId="40.[94,623,214,1763]" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">
We found five roosting groups of 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFBBFF88FDE221CDFE808D2F" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1838" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Saccopteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilineata">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBBFF88FDE221CDFE808D2F" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">Saccopteryx bilineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at Paracou. All of these occupied moreÂ­orÂ­less vertical cavities (by contrast with the essentially horizontal chambers typically used by 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFBBFF88FEC82645FDB28D55" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[314,569,1111,1134]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Cormura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brevirostris">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBBFF88FEC82645FDB28D55" box="[314,569,1111,1134]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">Cormura brevirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="00B03685FFBBFF88FFAC2666FF548DB0" authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1867" box="[94,223,1140,1163]" class="Mammalia" family="Emballonuridae" genus="Peropteryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="40" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F5C49114FFBBFF88FFAC2666FF548DB0" box="[94,223,1140,1163]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="40">Peropteryx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp.) with notÂ­quiteÂ­completely dark interiors (the roosting bats were usually just visible without illumination), but other roost characteristics differed. One roost was in a 2Â­mÂ­high chimney, open above and below, formed by the fused buttresses of a large tree (fig. 3); another was in the semicylindrical basal opening of a central cavity that extended far up into the trunk of a much smallÂ­ er tree (fig. 21); two were in the open bases of hollow trees big enough for a grown man to stand inside; and the fifth was an open cleft, 12 m above the ground at its lowest point, in the trunk of another big tree (accessed by climbing a rope). Roosting groups that we were able to count varied from one to five individuals. Two individuals that we found roosting alone were both adult males. One group of five that we captured in its entirety consisted of two adult males, two adult females, and one juvenile.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
